Nykka's Python Project: Run simple linear regression¶

Tasks:¶

  • Provides insights about the company's sales and marketing practices.
  • Explore the relationship between radio promotion budget and sales.

  • Provide a clear understanding of the relationship between types of marketing campaigns and the revenue generated as a result of this investment.

  • The dataset provided includes information about marketing campaigns across TV, radio, and social media, as well as how much revenue in sales was generated from these campaigns.

  • Stakeholder will make decisions about where to focus future marketing resources.

Step 3. Model Building¶

Select only the columns that are needed for the model.¶

In [12]:
# Select relevant columns
# Prepare for regression by saving resulting DataFrame in a new variable.
ols_data = data[["Radio", "Sales"]]

Create a linear regression formula for modeling the relationship between the 'Sales' and 'Radio'.¶

In [14]:
# Write the linear regression formula
# Save it in a variable
ols_formula = "Sales ~ Radio"

Use Ordinary Least Squares (OLS) approach for linear regression.¶

In [15]:
# Use OLS
OLS = ols(formula = ols_formula, data = ols_data)

Create a linear regression model for the data and fit the model to the data.¶

In [16]:
# Fit the model to the data
# Save the fitted model in a variable
model = OLS.fit()

Check the normality assumption.¶

First, I will get the residuals from the model.

In [19]:
# Get the residuals from the model
residuals = model.resid

Then , I will plot the distribution of the residuals.

In [20]:
# Create histogram of the distribution of the residuals
fig = sns.histplot(residuals)
fig.set_xlabel("Residual Value")
fig.set_title("Histogram of Residuals")
plt.show()

Question 10: Based on the preceding visualization, what do you observe about the distribution of the residuals?¶

  • Based on the histogram, the distribution of the residuals is mostly normal.
  • This indicates that the assumption of normality is likely met.

Create a Q-Q plot to confirm the assumption of normality.¶

In [21]:
# Create a Q-Q plot 
sm.qqplot(residuals, line='s')
plt.title("Q-Q plot of Residuals")
plt.show()

Question 11: Is the assumption of normality met?¶

  • The Q-Q plot shows that the points closely follow a straight diagonal line and is trending upward.
  • This confirms that the normality assumption is met.

Check the assumptions of independent observation and homoscedasticity.¶

First, I will get the fitted values from the model.

In [22]:
# Get fitted values
fitted_values = model.predict(ols_data["Radio"])

Then, I will create a scatterplot of the residuals against the fitted values.

In [23]:
# Create a scatterplot of residuals against fitted values
fig = sns.scatterplot(x=fitted_values, y=residuals)
fig.axhline(0)
fig.set_xlabel("Fitted Values")
fig.set_ylabel("Residuals")
plt.show()

Question 12: Are the assumptions of independent observation and homoscedasticity met?¶

  • The scatterplot displays the points as a cloud-like resemblance that do not follow an explicit pattern.
  • I can say that it appears that the independent observation assumption has not been violated.
  • Since the residuals seemed to be randomly spaced out, the homoscedasticity assumption seems to be met.

Findings¶

Takeaways:

  • This project helps me to see that data visualizations and exploratory data analysis can be used to check if linear regression is an effective for modeling the relationship between two variables.
  • The results of a linear regression model can be used to express the relationship between two variables.



What results can be presented from this lab?

  • The result of this simple linear regression model shows the y-intercept is 41.5326 and the slope is 8.1733.
  • This points to that a budget of 1 million dollars in radio promotion, can help a company's sales increase by 8.1733 million dollars on average.



More Interpretations:

  • Null hypothesis:
    • There is no relationship between radio promotion budget and sales when the slope is zero.
  • Alternative hypothesis:
    • There is a relationship between radio promotion budget and sales when the slope is not zero.
  • Result:
    • I will reject the null hypothesis since there seemed to be a relationship between radio promotion budget and sales.
  • The results are statistically significant: P-value of 0.000 is less than the common significance level of 0.05.
  • There is a low probability of observing data as extreme or more extreme than this dataset when the null hypothesis is true.
  • The slope of the line of best fit that resulted from the regression model is approximate and subject to uncertainty (not the exact value).
  • The 95% confidence interval for the slope is from 7.791 to 8.555.
  • There is a 95% probability that the interval [7.791, 8.555] contains the true value for the slope.



How would you frame your findings to external stakeholders?

  • The regression analysis shows a notable relationship between radio promotion budget and sales, with a p-value of 0.000 and standard error of 0.194.
  • For companies represented by this data, an increase in radio promotion budget could be associated an increase in sales.
